PROPOSED PARENTING TIME SCHEDULE
(Joint Physical Custody - Equal Time)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

I. PURPOSE AND GOALS

     This Parenting Time Schedule is designed to implement joint physical custody with equal parenting time (182.5 overnights per year each), as requested in Father's Motion to Modify Custody.

     GOALS:
     • Maximize the child's time with both parents
     • Provide consistency and predictability
     • Minimize transitions for the child
     • Ensure both parents remain actively involved in daily life
     • Comply with MCL 722.27a's presumption favoring parenting time
     • Serve the child's best interests

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

II. SCHEDULE OPTIONS

     Three schedule options are presented for the Court's consideration:

     OPTION 1: Week On / Week Off (Recommended for school-age children)
     OPTION 2: 2-2-3 Rotating Schedule (Provides more frequent contact)
     OPTION 3: 2-2-5-5 Rotating Schedule (Balance of consistency and frequency)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OPTION 1: WEEK ON / WEEK OFF SCHEDULE

A. Regular Schedule

     Week 1 (Father):
     Monday 9:00 AM through the following Monday 9:00 AM (7 days)

     Week 2 (Mother):
     Monday 9:00 AM through the following Monday 9:00 AM (7 days)

     The schedule alternates weekly throughout the year.

B. Annual Distribution

     • Father: 26 weeks per year = 182 overnights
     • Mother: 26 weeks per year = 183 overnights (in non-leap years)
     • This provides 49.86% / 50.14% time split (essentially equal)

C. Sample Calendar (February-March 2026)

     Week of Feb 10-16: Father
     Week of Feb 17-23: Mother
     Week of Feb 24-Mar 2: Father
     Week of Mar 3-9: Mother
     Week of Mar 10-16: Father
     Week of Mar 17-23: Mother

D. Advantages

     • Simple and easy to remember
     • Minimizes transitions (only one exchange per week)
     • Allows each parent full week of uninterrupted time
     • Works well for school-age children
     • Reduces conflict at exchanges

E. Considerations

     • Longer time between contacts with each parent
     • May be challenging for younger children (age 5)
     • Can be modified to 4-3 or 5-2 schedule if needed

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OPTION 2: 2-2-3 ROTATING SCHEDULE (RECOMMENDED)

A. Regular Schedule

     Week A:
          Monday-Tuesday: Father (2 days) [6:00 PM Sunday through 6:00 PM Tuesday]
          Wednesday-Thursday: Mother (2 days) [6:00 PM Tuesday through 6:00 PM Thursday]
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday: Father (3 days) [6:00 PM Thursday through 6:00 PM Sunday]

     Week B:
          Monday-Tuesday: Mother (2 days) [6:00 PM Sunday through 6:00 PM Tuesday]
          Wednesday-Thursday: Father (2 days) [6:00 PM Tuesday through 6:00 PM Thursday]
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday: Mother (3 days) [6:00 PM Thursday through 6:00 PM Sunday]

     The schedule alternates between Week A and Week B throughout the year.

B. Annual Distribution

     • Father: 182.5 overnights per year (50.0%)
     • Mother: 182.5 overnights per year (50.0%)
     • Perfect equality

C. Sample Calendar (February 2026)

     Week A (Feb 10-16):
          Mon-Tue (Feb 10-11): Father
          Wed-Thu (Feb 12-13): Mother
          Fri-Sat-Sun (Feb 14-16): Father

     Week B (Feb 17-23):
          Mon-Tue (Feb 17-18): Mother
          Wed-Thu (Feb 19-20): Father
          Fri-Sat-Sun (Feb 21-23): Mother

     Week A (Feb 24-Mar 2):
          Mon-Tue (Feb 24-25): Father
          Wed-Thu (Feb 26-27): Mother
          Fri-Sat-Sun (Feb 28-Mar 2): Father

D. Advantages

     • True 50/50 split (182.5 overnights each)
     • Frequent contact with both parents (no more than 2-3 days apart)
     • Works well for young children (age 5)
     • Each parent gets every other weekend
     • Predictable pattern

E. Considerations

     • More frequent exchanges (4 per week)
     • Requires cooperation and good communication
     • More complex to remember initially
     • Works best when parents live in close proximity

F. THIS IS THE RECOMMENDED SCHEDULE for Lincoln (age 5) because:
     • Maintains frequent contact with both parents
     • Minimizes separation anxiety for young child
     • Ensures neither parent is absent from child's life for extended periods
     • Addresses harm from 329+ days of deprivation by ensuring regular contact

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OPTION 3: 2-2-5-5 ROTATING SCHEDULE

A. Regular Schedule

     Week A:
          Monday-Tuesday: Father (2 days) [6:00 PM Sunday through 6:00 PM Tuesday]
          Wednesday-Thursday: Mother (2 days) [6:00 PM Tuesday through 6:00 PM Thursday]
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday-Monday-Tuesday: Father (5 days) [6:00 PM Thursday through 6:00 PM Tuesday]

     Week B:
          Wednesday-Thursday: Father (2 days) [6:00 PM Tuesday through 6:00 PM Thursday]
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday-Monday-Tuesday: Mother (5 days) [6:00 PM Thursday through 6:00 PM Tuesday]

     The schedule alternates between Week A and Week B throughout the year.

B. Annual Distribution

     • Father: 182.5 overnights per year (50.0%)
     • Mother: 182.5 overnights per year (50.0%)
     • Perfect equality

C. Sample Calendar (February 2026)

     Week A (Feb 10-18):
          Mon-Tue (Feb 10-11): Father
          Wed-Thu (Feb 12-13): Mother
          Fri-Sat-Sun-Mon-Tue (Feb 14-18): Father (5 days)

     Week B (Feb 19-Mar 2):
          Wed-Thu (Feb 19-20): Father
          Fri-Sat-Sun-Mon-Tue (Feb 21-25): Mother (5 days)
          [Cycle repeats]

D. Advantages

     • True 50/50 split (182.5 overnights each)
     • Longer stretches of time with each parent (5-day blocks)
     • Fewer exchanges than 2-2-3 schedule
     • Each parent gets every other weekend plus mid-week time

E. Considerations

     • Slightly more complex pattern to remember
     • 5-day stretches may be long for young child
     • Still requires cooperation and communication

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

III. HOLIDAY AND VACATION SCHEDULE (APPLIES TO ALL OPTIONS)

A. General Principles

     1. Holiday schedule takes precedence over regular schedule
     2. Holiday time counts toward the parent's annual overnight total
     3. Regular schedule resumes after holiday period ends
     4. Parents alternate holidays on odd/even year basis
     5. Make-up time may be provided if holiday significantly disrupts regular time

B. Alternating Holidays

     1. ODD YEARS WITH FATHER, EVEN YEARS WITH MOTHER:

          • New Year's Day: December 31 at 6:00 PM through January 1 at 6:00 PM

          • Easter: Saturday before Easter at 6:00 PM through Easter Monday at 6:00 PM

          • Memorial Day: Saturday before Memorial Day at 6:00 PM through Memorial Day at 6:00 PM

          • July 4th: July 3 at 6:00 PM through July 5 at 6:00 PM

          • Labor Day: Saturday before Labor Day at 6:00 PM through Labor Day at 6:00 PM

          • Thanksgiving: Wednesday before Thanksgiving at 6:00 PM through Sunday after Thanksgiving at 6:00 PM

     2. EVEN YEARS WITH FATHER, ODD YEARS WITH MOTHER:

          • Spring Break: First day of spring break at 6:00 PM through last day of spring break at 6:00 PM (full week)

          • Halloween: October 31 from 4:00 PM through 8:00 PM (trick-or-treating hours only; child returns to regularly scheduled parent at 8:00 PM)

          • Christmas: December 24 at 6:00 PM through December 26 at 6:00 PM

C. Special Days (Every Year)

     1. Child's Birthday:
          • ODD YEARS: Father has child on birthday (birthday date at 4:00 PM through next day at 8:00 AM)
          • EVEN YEARS: Mother has child on birthday (birthday date at 4:00 PM through next day at 8:00 AM)
          • Birthday does not replace regular parenting time; it is in addition to regular schedule

     2. Father's Day:
          • Father has child every Father's Day weekend (Saturday at 9:00 AM through Sunday at 6:00 PM)
          • Supersedes regular schedule

     3. Mother's Day:
          • Mother has child every Mother's Day weekend (Saturday at 9:00 AM through Sunday at 6:00 PM)
          • Supersedes regular schedule

D. Summer Vacation (June 1 - August 31)

     1. Each parent is entitled to two (2) weeks of uninterrupted summer vacation parenting time with the child.

     2. Summer vacation weeks:
          • Must be selected by May 1 each year
          • Father selects first in odd years; Mother selects first in even years
          • Cannot conflict with other parent's selected weeks
          • Must be reasonable (cannot take last two weeks of summer, etc.)

     3. Notice requirements:
          • Selected weeks must be provided in writing to other parent by May 15
          • Include specific dates (start date and end date)
          • If no selection made by May 15, parent forfeits first selection right

     4. Summer vacation time counts toward annual overnight total

     5. Regular schedule resumes after summer vacation weeks end

E. Winter Break (December)

     1. Winter break shall be divided as follows:

          ODD YEARS:
          • Father: First half of winter break (school dismissal through December 26 at noon)
          • Mother: Second half of winter break (December 26 at noon through school resumption)

          EVEN YEARS:
          • Mother: First half of winter break (school dismissal through December 26 at noon)
          • Father: Second half of winter break (December 26 at noon through school resumption)

     2. This schedule coordinates with the alternating Christmas holiday

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

IV. EXCHANGE PROCEDURES

A. Exchange Times and Locations

     1. All exchanges shall occur at [TO BE SPECIFIED: police station, neutral public location, school, other agreed location].

     2. Alternative arrangements: Parties may agree to alternative exchange locations (e.g., school, daycare, other parent's home) if they can communicate cooperatively.

B. Responsibility for Transportation

     1. The parent beginning parenting time is responsible for picking up the child at the exchange location at the scheduled time.

     2. The parent ending parenting time shall have the child ready at the exchange location at the scheduled time.

     3. Each parent is responsible for transporting the child to their own residence after pickup.

C. Exchange Guidelines

     1. BE ON TIME: Both parents shall arrive at exchanges on time. Being more than 15 minutes late without communication constitutes a violation.

     2. Child Ready: The child shall be:
          • Clean and dressed appropriately for weather
          • Fed (if exchange occurs at mealtime)
          • Rested and in good health
          • Has all necessary items (clothing, medications, special items)

     3. Child's Belongings: Each parent shall send with the child:
          • Sufficient clothing for the parenting time period
          • Any prescription medications with written instructions
          • Comfort items (favorite toy, blanket, etc.)
          • School backpack and homework (if applicable)
          • Any special equipment (e.g., car seat, if needed)

     4. Return of Belongings: Items sent with the child shall be returned with the child at the next exchange.

D. Conduct at Exchanges

     1. Professional Behavior: Both parents shall conduct themselves in a professional, businesslike manner at exchanges.

     2. No Confrontation: There shall be no arguing, confrontation, yelling, or hostile behavior at exchanges.

     3. No Negative Comments: Neither parent shall make negative comments about the other parent at exchanges or in the child's presence.

     4. Brief and Businesslike: Exchanges should be brief. Essential information may be communicated, but extended conversations should occur by email/text outside the child's presence.

     5. Focus on Child: The focus of the exchange shall be the child, not the parents' conflict.

E. Late or Missed Exchanges

     1. If Unavoidably Late: Parent must notify other parent immediately if running late. Provide estimated arrival time.

     2. If More Than 30 Minutes Late Without Notice: Other parent may leave and parenting time is forfeited for that period.

     3. If Parent Fails to Appear: Document the failure (date, time, location). Report to Court if pattern develops.

     4. Repeated Failures: Three (3) or more missed exchanges without legitimate excuse shall be grounds for contempt proceedings and modification of schedule.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

V. COMMUNICATION

A. Between Parents

     1. Method: All communication regarding the child shall be via [text message / email / co-parenting app such as OurFamilyWizard or TalkingParents] or telephone for urgent matters.

     2. Tone: Communication shall be:
          • Respectful
          • Businesslike
          • Focused on the child's needs
          • Free of blame, accusations, or hostility

     3. Response Time: Each parent shall respond to communications regarding the child within 24 hours (or sooner if urgent).

     4. Topics: Communication should address:
          • Child's health and medical needs
          • School information and activities
          • Schedule changes or conflicts
          • Child's emotional or behavioral concerns
          • Logistics (exchanges, belongings, etc.)

     5. Prohibited Topics: Do not use child-related communication to:
          • Argue about adult issues
          • Make accusations
          • Discuss child support or financial matters (use separate communication)
          • Harass or threaten the other parent

B. Between Child and Other Parent

     1. Right to Contact: The child has the right to communicate with the other parent during parenting time.

     2. Frequency: Each parent shall facilitate at least one (1) telephone or video call per day between the child and the other parent at a reasonable time.

     3. Call Duration: Calls should be reasonable in length (typically 10-15 minutes).

     4. Call Times: Calls should occur at reasonable times:
          • Not during meals (unless agreed)
          • Not during homework time
          • Not immediately before bedtime
          • Generally between 6:00 PM and 8:00 PM

     5. Privacy: The child shall have privacy during calls. Neither parent shall monitor, record, or interfere with calls.

     6. No Pressure: Neither parent shall pressure the child to call or communicate. The child should feel free to decline calls if engaged in activities.

     7. Emergency Contact: Each parent shall ensure the child can reach the other parent in an emergency at any time.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

VI. SCHOOL AND ACTIVITIES

A. School Involvement

     1. Both parents have equal right to:
          • Attend parent-teacher conferences
          • Volunteer at school
          • Attend school events (plays, concerts, awards ceremonies)
          • Receive school communications
          • Access school records

     2. Each parent shall ensure the child attends school on time when school falls during their parenting time.

     3. School communications (report cards, progress reports, school calendar) shall be shared with both parents.

B. Extracurricular Activities

     1. Joint Decision: Enrollment in extracurricular activities requires joint agreement (as part of legal custody).

     2. Both parents may attend: Both parents have the right to attend the child's extracurricular activities (games, performances, etc.) regardless of which parent's time it falls on.

     3. Transportation: The parent exercising parenting time is responsible for transporting the child to/from activities that occur during their time.

     4. Cost: Costs of activities shall be shared equally (or as otherwise agreed).

C. Medical Appointments

     1. Routine Appointments: May be scheduled by the parent exercising parenting time at that time.

     2. Major Medical Decisions: Require joint agreement (as part of legal custody).

     3. Information Sharing: Both parents shall be informed of all medical appointments, diagnoses, and treatments.

     4. Emergency Medical: Each parent has authority to seek emergency medical treatment during their parenting time and shall notify other parent as soon as practical.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

VII. MAKEUP PARENTING TIME (329 DAYS OWED TO FATHER)

A. Legal Basis

     Father has been wrongfully deprived of 329+ days of parenting time from March 2024 through February 2026. Makeup time is required by MCL 722.27a(3) and Michigan case law.

B. Amount

     329 days of makeup parenting time

C. Scheduling

     1. Makeup time shall be scheduled at Father's discretion over the next 18 months (through August 11, 2027).

     2. Makeup blocks shall be no less than three (3) consecutive days each.

     3. Father shall provide Mother with at least 14 days' written notice of each makeup block.

     4. Makeup time is IN ADDITION to regular parenting time. It does not replace Father's regular time.

D. Examples of Makeup Blocks

     • Week-long blocks (7 days each): 47 weeks = 329 days
     • Extended weekends (4 days each): 82 blocks = 328 days
     • Mix of week-long and weekend blocks

E. Priority

     1. Makeup time takes precedence over Mother's regular parenting time when scheduled.

     2. Mother shall fully cooperate with makeup time scheduling and shall not interfere.

F. Documentation

     Father shall maintain a log of makeup time exercised. Once 329 days have been completed, obligation is satisfied.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

VIII. MODIFICATIONS AND DISPUTES

A. Modifications by Agreement

     1. The parties may agree to modify the schedule on a case-by-case basis (e.g., switch weekends due to work conflict, family event, etc.).

     2. All agreements to modify should be in writing (email or text) to avoid misunderstandings.

     3. Modifications by agreement do not change the underlying order.

B. Dispute Resolution

     1. Good Faith Efforts: Parties shall make good faith efforts to resolve disputes regarding the schedule.

     2. Communication: Attempt to resolve disputes through respectful communication.

     3. Mediation: If unable to resolve, parties may agree to mediation.

     4. Court Intervention: If unable to resolve through other means, a party may file a motion with the Court. However, Court intervention should be last resort.

C. Enforcement

     1. Both parties shall comply strictly with the schedule.

     2. Willful violations may result in:
          • Contempt proceedings
          • Makeup time for parent denied time
          • Modification of schedule
          • Attorney fees and sanctions
          • Change of custody

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

IX. MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS

A. Flexibility and Cooperation

     While the schedule is binding, both parents are encouraged to be flexible and cooperative when reasonable circumstances arise. The child's best interests are served when parents can work together.

B. Priority

     The child's needs and wellbeing shall be the priority at all times. The schedule should serve the child, not the parents' conflict.

C. No Interference

     Neither parent shall interfere with the other parent's time with the child. Interference includes:
     • Calling/texting excessively during other parent's time
     • Making plans during other parent's time without permission
     • Showing up unannounced during other parent's time
     • Encouraging child to refuse parenting time
     • Making negative comments about other parent

D. Right to First Refusal (OPTIONAL)

     [If the Court includes this provision]: If either parent will be unavailable for more than 4 hours during their parenting time, they shall offer the other parent the right of first refusal to care for the child during that time before using third-party childcare.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

X. CONCLUSION

     This Parenting Time Schedule is designed to implement joint physical custody with equal parenting time, ensuring that Lincoln maintains strong, healthy relationships with both parents.

     The recommended schedule (Option 2: 2-2-3 Rotating) provides:
     • Perfect 50/50 time split (182.5 overnights each)
     • Frequent contact with both parents (no more than 2-3 days apart)
     • Predictability and consistency
     • Age-appropriate structure for a 5-year-old child
     • Compliance with MCL 722.27a

     This schedule will restore the father-child relationship damaged by 329+ days of deprivation and ensure Lincoln's right to both parents is protected.

